      "title": "Module 2: Behavioural activation",
      "text": "CBT has a precise tool for low, flat, restless states: behavioural activation. The principle is counter-intuitive but reliable — action comes before motivation, not after. You don't wait to feel like doing something; you do a small something, and the feeling follows. Smokers had it backwards: they used the cigarette as a tiny \"activity\" to fill the gap, which kept them passive. You're going to fill the gap with genuine, even tiny, engagement, which builds momentum instead of draining it.\n\nThis doesn't mean every idle minute must be productive. It means having a ready list of small, satisfying things to reach for when restlessness hits, so the moment has somewhere to go besides the old reflex. A two-minute walk, a few pages of a book, a message to a friend, a quick tidy, a stretch, a hobby you keep meaning to pick up. Small actions, reliably done, lift a flat mood far better than a cigarette ever pretended to."
